<p>The <strong><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_fixed_cost">Average Fixed Cost</a> Curve</strong> is a L-shape curve because the <em>Fixed Costs</em> are <strong>fixed</strong> then the AFC <strong>decrease</strong> when the <em>Quantity of Output</em> <strong>increase</strong>. This has an important application in the study of <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_monopoly">natural monopolies</a>. </p>
<p>The <strong><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_variable_cost">Average Variable Cost</a> Curve</strong> is a J-shape curve because the <em><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diminishing_returns">diminishing marginal product</a></em>. The marginal cost increases with the quantity produced. When a <strong>small amount</strong> is produced, <em>few workers</em> are involved, and much of the <em>equipment is not used</em>. Because you can easily put these <em>idle resources to use</em>, the marginal product of <em>an additional worker</em> is <strong>large</strong>, and the marginal cost of <em>an additional output</em> is <strong>small</strong>. By contrast, when a <strong>large amount</strong> is produced, the <em>space is filled with workers</em>, and most of the <em>equipment is fully utilized</em>. It can produce more by<em>(adding workers</em>, but these new workers have to work in crowed conditions and may have to wait to use the equipment. Therefore, when the <em>amount produced is already high</em>, the marginal product of <em>an additional worker</em> is <strong>low</strong>, and the marginal cost of <em>an extra output</em> is <strong>large</strong>.</p>
<p>The <strong><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_total_cost">Average Total Cost</a> Curve</strong> is a U-shape curve because <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_fixed_cost">Average Fixed Cost</a> always declines as output rises because the fixed cost is spread over a larger number of units and <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_variable_cost">Average Variable Cost</a> typically rises as output increases because of <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diminishing_returns">diminishing marginal product</a>.</p>
<p>The <strong>lowest point of the average total cost</strong> is the most efficient point to perform the production. Sometimes this is called, <strong><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minimum_efficient_scale">efficient scale</a></strong> because is the quantity of output that minimizes average total cost. The <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marginal_cost">Marginal Cost</a> Curve intersect the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_total_cost">Average Total Cost</a> Curve precisely at that point. Whenever <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marginal_cost">Marginal Cost</a> is <strong>less than</strong> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_total_cost">Average Total Cost</a>, <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_total_cost">Average Total Cost</a> is <strong>falling</strong>. Whenever <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marginal_cost">Marginal Cost</a> is <strong>greater than</strong> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_total_cost">Average Total Cost</a>, <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_total_cost">Average Total Cost</a> is <strong>rising</strong>. At low levels of production, the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marginal_cost">Marginal Cost</a> is <em>below</em> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_total_cost">Average Total Cost</a>, so <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_total_cost">Average Total Cost</a> is <strong>falling</strong>. But after the two curves cross, <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marginal_cost">Marginal Cost</a>  increases <em>above</em> the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_total_cost">Average Total Cost</a>. For the reason just discussed,  <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_total_cost">Average Total Cost</a> should begin to <em>rise</em> to that level of production. Therefore, this point of intersection is
the <strong>minimum average total cost</strong>.</p>

